    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.19.2"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">2</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">CHICAGO ∙ BOSTON ∙ ATLANTA ∙ DALLAS ∙ SAN FRANCISCO ∙ LONDON ∙ TORONTO ∙ BOMBAY ∙ CALCUTTA ∙ MADRAS ∙ MELBOURNE ∙ SHANGHAI ∙ MANILA
                
                    THE MACMILLAN COMPANY
                
                    CABLE ADDRESS
                    PACHAMAC NEW YORK</hi>
                
                    <hi rend="italics">Publishers</hi>
                
                    <hi rend="caps">TELEPHONE
                    ALGONQUIN 4-2100
                
                    SIXTY ∙ FIFTH AVENUE ∙ NEW YORK
                
                    GEORGE P. BRETT, JR., PRESIDENT
                    L. J. LUCAS, SECRETARY
                    R. M. BRETT, TREASURER
                
                    H. S. LATHAM VICE PRESIDENT
                    IN CHARGE OF ALL TRADE DEPARTMENTS
                    A. H. NELSON VICE PRESIDENT
                    IN CHARGE OF ALL EDUCATIONAL DEPARTMENTS</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>April 15, 1940.</dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I am so glad, on my return from a two months' absence, to find your letter of April 2nd, indicating that you are making happy and satisfactory progress with <hi rend="caps">THE SONG OF JED SMITH</hi>. Some-how, I had a hunch all along that this was going to be one of your best books, if not your best, and I am so pleased that you begin to feel confident about it yourself. Manuscript in November means publication I suppose the early part of the new year. Let's hope that by then the world situation will have improved a little so that people will have more time, more inclination, more heart for the reading of books.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>With my best of greetings,</salute>
                    <salute>Very sincerely yours,</salute>
                    <signed>H.S. Latham</signed>
                
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Branson, Mo.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                
                    <note>HSL.KK</note>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
